We are seeing problems where async functions are holding onto references thereby causing large amounts of memory not to be released. This is due to the way call stacks are effectively reversed for synchronous continuations. I think the below example shows that this can happen with parameters (which become fields in the state machine) and value types (which are not cleaned up unlike other locals). I've prototyped a fix for the parameter issue - https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/commit/e4f30581725718f2dac231d58e44cdd8215736cd. Joint work with @lazy.

**Version Used**: 
6.0

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```
while (true)
{
    await Task1();
    Check(arrayInMem: false);
}

static bool Check(bool? arrayInMem = null)
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
        GC.Collect();
    var totalMem = GC.GetTotalMemory(true);
    var mem = totalMem > 1_000_000_000;
    var weakref = Program.WeakRef.TryGetTarget(out _);
    if (mem != weakref)
        throw new Exception("mem check and weakref checks do not match");
    if (arrayInMem.HasValue && (arrayInMem.Value ^ mem))
        throw new Exception($"Failed check, should have returned in mem = {arrayInMem.Value}");
    return mem;
}

static async Task Task1()
{
    await Task2();
    // this shows 'reversed' stack -> Console.WriteLine(Environment.StackTrace);
    // At this point a developer would reasonably expect the array to be collectable
    Console.BackgroundColor = Check() ? ConsoleColor.Red : ConsoleColor.Black;
    Console.Write(Check() ? "*" : ".");
    await Task.Yield(); // prevents mem leaking to Main
}

static async Task Task2()
{
    Check(arrayInMem: false);
    var localMem = new byte[1_000_000_000];
    Program.WeakRef.SetTarget(localMem);
    Check(arrayInMem: true);

    await Task3(localMem); // pass new byte[] { localMem[0] } here to stop testing parameters

    // this causes failures even when the parameter issue is fixed in the compiler
    ReturnsTuple(localMem); // comment this out to stop testing value types
}

static async Task<int> Task3(byte[] mem)
{
    await Task.Delay(1);
    return mem[0];
}

static (byte[], int[]) ReturnsTuple(byte[] mem)
{
    return (mem, new int[] { mem[0] } );
}

public partial class Program
{
    static WeakReference<byte[]?> WeakRef = new WeakReference<byte[]?>(null);
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:

Memory can be freed in Task1 as soon as Task2 completes so you would see a row of dots

**Actual Behavior**:

Memory is not freed until the Task.Yield breaks the synchronous continuations, so you see a row of red asterisks

